Protocols for study of
Trans-ancestry concordance of hepatic fat genetic architecture validates the cardiometabolic criteria for metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease

Step 1: Ancestry-specific GWAS
Tools: GCTA-fastGWA

1.1 GWAS in the European population
Four models were analyzed:
PDFF
PDFF_BMI_adjusted
PDFF_WFM_adjusted
PDFF_VAT_adjusted

Imputed genotype dosages in BGEN format were used as input. Association analyses were performed using fastGWA mixed linear models with a sparse GRM.

gcta64 --mbgen ${bgen_merge_list} --sample ${sample_file} --grm-sparse ${sparse_grm} --fastGWA-mlm --nofilter --pheno ${pheno_file} --mpheno 1 --qcovar ${qcovar_file} --covar ${covar_file} --thread-num 48 --out ${output_prefix}

1.2 GWAS in the East Asian population
Analyses were performed under unadjusted and BMI-adjusted models.

Unadjusted model:
LA_mean_log

BMI-adjusted models:
LA_mean_log
LS_diff_log
LS_ratio_log

Imputed genotype dosages in BGEN format were used as input. Association analyses were performed using fastGWA mixed linear models with a sparse GRM.

gcta64 --mbgen ${bgen_merge_list} --sample ${sample_file} --grm-sparse ${sparse_grm} --fastGWA-mlm --nofilter --pheno ${pheno_file} --mpheno ${phenotype_index} --qcovar ${qcovar_file} --thread-num 48 --out ${output_prefix}


Step 2: Lead variant identification by LD clumping
Tools: PLINK

Lead variants were identified from ancestry-specific GWAS summary statistics using LD clumping. Clumping was performed separately for each phenotype and chromosome using ancestry-matched reference genotype data.

Clumping criteria:
Genome-wide significance threshold: P < 5e-8
LD threshold: r2 < 0.01
Window size: 500 kb

2.1 Clumping in the European population
Phenotypes:
PDFF
PDFF_BMI_adjusted
PDFF_WFM_adjusted
PDFF_VAT_adjusted

plink --bfile ${reference_chr} --clump-p1 5e-8 --clump-p2 5e-8 --clump-r2 0.01 --clump-kb 500 --clump ${gwas_summary_statistics} --clump-snp-field SNP --clump-field P --memory 50000 --out ${output_prefix}

2.2 Clumping in the East Asian population
Phenotypes:
LA_mean_log
LS_diff_log
LS_ratio_log

plink --bfile ${reference_chr} --clump-p1 5e-8 --clump-p2 5e-8 --clump-r2 0.01 --clump-kb 500 --clump ${gwas_summary_statistics} --clump-snp-field SNP --clump-field P --memory 50000 --out ${output_prefix}


Step 3: Trans-ancestry meta-analysis
Tools: METAL

A fixed-effects inverse-variance-weighted meta-analysis was performed using METAL. The METAL command file was first written as a text file and then executed in batch mode.

METAL command file:
MARKER   SNP
SCHEME   STDERR
AVERAGEFREQ   ON
FREQLABEL   AF1
ALLELE   A1 A2
EFFECT   BETA
PVALUE   P
STDERR   SE
PROCESS   ${EAS_GWAS_summary_statistics}
PROCESS   ${EUR_GWAS_summary_statistics}
OUTFILE   ${output_prefix} .TBL
ANALYZE   HETEROGENEITY
Quit

printf "%s" "$meta_cmd" > "${metal_command_file}"

METAL execution:
metal ${metal_command_file}


Step 4: Trans-ancestry genetic effect correlation
Tools: Popcorn

The global trans-ancestry genetic effect correlation was estimated using Popcorn based on summary statistics from the East Asian and European GWAS.

popcorn fit -v 2 --cfile ${cross_population_score_file} --sfile1 ${EUR_summary_statistics} --sfile2 ${EAS_summary_statistics} --gen_effect ${output_file}


Step 5: Alcohol-stratified GWAS
Tools: GCTA-fastGWA

To assess the impact of alcohol consumption on genetic heterogeneity, GWAS was repeated in the European population after stratification by drinking status.

Drinking groups:
never drinkers
light-to-moderate drinkers
heavy drinkers

Association analyses were performed using fastGWA mixed linear models with the same phenotype and covariate settings as in the main European GWAS, while restricting the analysis to each subgroup separately.

gcta64 --mbgen ${bgen_merge_list} --sample ${sample_file} --grm-sparse ${sparse_grm} --fastGWA-mlm --nofilter --pheno ${pheno_file} --mpheno 1 --qcovar ${qcovar_file} --covar ${covar_file} --keep ${subgroup_sample_file} --thread-num 48 --out ${output_prefix}


Step 6: Genetic correlation analysis
Tools: LDSC

Genetic correlations between hepatic fat content and cardiometabolic risk factors were estimated using linkage disequilibrium score regression. Analyses were performed separately in each ancestry using ancestry-matched LD score reference panels.

Cardiometabolic traits included:
BMI
GLU
HbA1c
SBP
DBP
TC
TG
HDL-C
LDL-C
Urate

ldsc.py --ref-ld-chr ${ldscore_reference} --w-ld-chr ${ldscore_reference} --rg ${HFC_sumstats},${CMRF_sumstats_1},${CMRF_sumstats_2},${CMRF_sumstats_3},${CMRF_sumstats_4},${CMRF_sumstats_5},${CMRF_sumstats_6},${CMRF_sumstats_7},${CMRF_sumstats_8},${CMRF_sumstats_9},${CMRF_sumstats_10} --out ${output_prefix}


Step 7: Cell-type enrichment analysis
Tools: scDRS

Cell-type enrichment analysis was performed using scDRS with human single-cell RNA-seq reference data. Gene sets derived from hepatic fat GWAS were used to compute disease relevance scores across cell types.

scdrs compute-score --h5ad-file ${single_cell_reference} --h5ad-species human --cov-file ${covariate_file} --gs-file ${gene_set_file} --gs-species human --ctrl-match-opt mean_var --weight-opt vs --adj-prop None --flag-filter-data True --flag-raw-count True --n-ctrl 1000 --flag-return-ctrl-raw-score False --flag-return-ctrl-norm-score True --out-folder ${output_folder}


Step 8: Polygenic risk score construction
Tools: PLINK, BOLT-LMM, GCTA-COJO

8.1 Genome-wide PRS
HapMap3 variants were first extracted from the European genotype data and used as the model SNP set for BOLT-LMM. Joint effect estimates were then obtained with the predBetasFile option and used as SNP weights for PRS calculation.

bolt --bed=${bed_files} --bim=${bim_files} --fam=${fam_file} --maxMissingPerSnp 1.0 --maxMissingPerIndiv 1.0 --modelSnps=${hapmap3_snp_list} --geneticMapFile=${genetic_map_file} --covarFile=${covar_file} --qCovarCol=${covariates} --phenoFile=${pheno_file} --phenoCol=PDFF --LDscoresFile=${ldscore_file} --LDscoresMatchBp --lmm --numThreads=6 --verboseStats --covarMaxLevels=30 --maxModelSnps=1500000 --statsFile=${stats_file} --predBetasFile=${predbeta_file}

PRS calculation was then performed chromosome by chromosome using PLINK score, followed by summation across chromosomes and Z-score standardization.

plink --bfile ${target_genotype_chr} --extract ${predbeta_file} --score ${predbeta_file} 1 5 7 sum --keep ${target_sample_file} --out ${output_prefix} --memory 8000 --allow-no-sex

8.2 Oligogenic PRS
Previously identified lead SNPs were extracted, and conditional joint analysis was performed using GCTA-COJO to obtain an independent SNP set and corresponding joint effect estimates. These SNPs were then used to construct the oligogenic PRS.

gcta64 --bfile ${reference_bfile} --cojo-file ${cojo_summary_file} --cojo-joint --cojo-collinear 0.95 --out ${output_prefix}


Step 9: Cross-ancestry PRS integration
Tools: PRS-CSx

PRS-CSx was used to integrate summary statistics from the European and East Asian GWAS. A grid search over different global shrinkage parameters was performed chromosome by chromosome.

python PRScsx.py --ref_dir=${reference_panel} --bim_prefix=${target_bfile_prefix} --sst_file=${EUR_sumstats},${EAS_sumstats} --n_gwas=${N_EUR},${N_EAS} --pop=EUR,EAS --phi=${phi} --chrom=${chr} --seed=42 --out_dir=${output_dir} --out_name=${output_name}


Step 10: PRS performance evaluation
Tools: R

The predictive performance of PRSs was evaluated using logistic regression models adjusted for age, sex, and the top 10 genetic principal components.

In the European population, the following outcomes were analyzed:
MASLD
Cirrhosis
Alcoholic cirrhosis
Broad cirrhosis
HCC
Liver-related death

In the Chinese population, only MASLD was analyzed.

The following PRSs were compared:
PRS_HFC_1.2M
PRS_HFC_58
PRS_HCC_5
PRS_NAFLD_17
PRS_NAFLD_68
PRS_cALT_77

For each outcome, a baseline model including covariates only was fitted first. Then, each PRS was added separately to the baseline model. PRSs were standardized before analysis.

glm(outcome ~ covariates, family=binomial)
glm(outcome ~ PRS + covariates, family=binomial)

The following metrics were calculated:
OR per standard deviation
AUC
Delta AUC compared with the baseline model
95% CI and P value for Delta AUC using DeLong test
Nagelkerke’s pseudo-R2
Net reclassification improvement (NRI)

roc(model$y, fitted(model))
roc.test(roc_prs, roc_base, method="delong")
nribin(event=outcome, p.std=fitted(base_model), p.new=fitted(prs_model), updown="diff", cut=0, niter=0)

Risk stratification analysis was additionally performed by dividing individuals into PRS deciles. Odds ratios were estimated for each decile using the bottom decile as the reference group. The top 5% and top 1% of the PRS distribution were further compared against the bottom 10%.

glm(outcome ~ prs_group + covariates, family=binomial)